When I started my content journey, barter collaborations genuinely helped me grow. And unknowingly, I was always a little strict about boundaries. But still, back then, people took advantage of my softness.

With time, I started working with agencies. At first, it felt like a big achievement—handling products from brands I grew up seeing. But slowly, reality hit.

Here’s what I’ve faced while working with agencies:

🔹 Endless edits for silly things – font speed, color, transition timing. Even after giving my best, they asked for multiple re-edits.

🔹 No creative freedom – I was told to say things I didn’t even believe in, just to match the brand brief. It felt forced, not honest.

🔹 POCs acting like gatekeepers – I used to think they were professionals. But later I realized many are just anyone with a contact. Your whole campaign depends on whether you get a decent POC or a toxic one.

🔹 Micromanagement for small creators – While big creators are allowed to be honest, we’re constantly told “change this, remove that.” And let’s be honest, most of these brands won’t even post our content on their own page.

🔹 Lack of respect for time – They want content within 1–3 days. But when it comes to paying us? They take 60–90 days just to send ₹1500.

🔹 Fake confirmation mails – I’ve received so many emails asking for my address after “shortlisting” me, and then I never get the product. Later they say the campaign got cancelled or I wasn’t selected. Then why take my details at all?

At this point, I’ve had enough.
I’m no longer working with any agency unless it aligns with my vision.

No more scripts.
No more compromises.
Only honest, meaningful content from here on.

Thank you to everyone who’s stood by me. 💙
#contentcreator #announcement #lifeofcontentcreator

⚠️Not Every Product Is Going To Suit Everyone! 

A couple of months ago, I received the Kiro PH Color Changing Lip Balm in PR, and that excitement of the newly launched product got me. It turned out to be my biggest mistake. 
Within a few days, I started feeling unusual irritation on my lips — especially the lower one — and couldn’t figure out what was triggering it.

I’m not blaming the product — it might just be one ingredient that didn’t suit my skin. That’s why I always say: not every product is meant for everyone, and it’s so important to listen to your body before things get worse.

I have super dry and temperamental lips — but I still can’t stand thick, waxy lip balms. I prefer lightweight balms that moisturize and actually lock in hydration without that heavy feeling.

So I immediately went back to something that always worked for me: Juicy Chemistry’s Tinted Lip Balm. I used it in the daytime for moisture and nourishment, and at night, I applied Boroline Antiseptic Cream to fasten the healing and peeling process.

And yes — I made sure to gently scrub off the dead skin every morning with just water. If you’ve ever used Boroline on your lips, you know how satisfying that next-morning peel is! 🙈💆🏻‍♀️

Grateful I listened to my skin on time. 💌

From being an under-confident girl who couldn’t even click a selfie in public…
To someone who celebrated her 26th birthday alone — with a wide smile, no panic, and a heart full of self-love.

This isn’t just a carousel of pictures. It’s a glimpse into something powerful — MY JOURNEY.✨

I used to always seek company to go out. Even when I stepped out alone, a part of me wished someone was there with me. But this birthday felt different.

I went for a solo movie. No friends, no plans — just me and a version I never expected to become. It wasn’t the version I was consciously building. It just… emerged. Unexpectedly. Quietly. Powerfully.

The first mirror selfie? I hesitated. My introvert self whispered, “Are you sure?”
But I clicked it.

The second one? Bold, fearless, free.
A quiet declaration:
"Yes, this is me. And I deserve to exist — confidently, unapologetically."

Later, I helped a guy who was struggling to take pictures of his girlfriend. In return, she clicked a few for me. When I told her it was my birthday, she asked, “Your friends must be waiting?”
I smiled: “No, I’m out alone. Just exploring.”
We had a quick chat and went our separate ways.

Because for the first time, I wasn’t hiding behind anyone.
I wasn’t waiting for someone else to show up for me.
I was the someone I needed all along.

I sat in the food court. Had my favourite KFC.
And not once did I feel sad or lonely.
Just me — whole, full, happy.

Some people were confused — “Why celebrate alone?”
They didn’t get it. Neither they liked it and they even told me that " I don't like it the way you're celebrating your birthday" but I did.
I liked it. I chose it.
For me.

No loud parties. No surprises.
But this birthday gave me something priceless —
Peace. Pride. Power.

Happy 26th birthday to me.
This year, I didn’t just grow older.
I grew into myself.

PS: For the first time ever, I didn’t cry on my birthday. 😭 (That’s a win-win situation anyway, right?)

#26AndEvolving #solobirthday #maincharacterenergy #fromselfdoubttoselflove #gratefulforeverything
